									<object width="500" height="308"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/a9GK1_Q0b7M&amp;rel=0&amp;egm=0&amp;showinfo=0&amp;fs=1"></param><param name="wmode" value="transparent"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/a9GK1_Q0b7M&amp;rel=0&amp;egm=0&amp;showinfo=0&amp;fs=1" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="500" height="308" allowFullScreen="true" wmode="transparent"></embed></object><br /><br />
									<p><strong>&#8220;Boardwalk Empire&#8221; (2010) — Arnold Rothstein knows</strong></p>
<p>Two things hit me hard in this clip:</p>
<p>1) The piece of music, straddling the line between ragtime and classical, sounds like it was written on a train by a guy who was real excited about his destination. I tried Shazamming it and SoundHounding it, so if anyone knows what it is, please tell.</p>
<p><strong>UPDATE:</strong> It&#8217;s <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/c2tzrq2394p9qlx/09%20Idle%20Dreams.mp3">&#8220;Idle Dreams&#8221; by George Gershwin</a>. Thanks, <a href="http://pchoooooooo.tumblr.com/post/1631490104/lonelysandwich-boardwalk-empire-2010">Fiberoptic Jesus</a>!</p>
<p>2) Rothstein&#8217;s last line. I won&#8217;t write it. Just watch.</p>
<p>Maybe Rothstein is the most perfect casting of the show. What a face that man has. That&#8217;s <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0836121/">Michael Stuhlbarg</a> from my favorite film of 2009 &#8220;A Serious Man&#8221;.</p>
<p>Also look out for Max Casella (Vinnie Delpino if you&#8217;re nasty), <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm1842344/">Vincent Piazza</a> as a dashing chlamydic Lucky Luciano, and <a href="http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0050737/">Edoardo Ballerini</a> looks exactly like I&#8217;d picture a character named Ignatius D&#8217;Alessio. Creepy in the best way.</p>
